# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: solid-state-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] where the *ni* are any integers, and **a***i* are *primitive translation vectors*, or *primitive vectors*, which lie in different directions (not necessarily mutually perpendicular) and span the lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The choice of primitive vectors for a given Bravais lattice is not unique.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] A fundamental aspect of any Bravais lattice is that, for any choice of direction, the lattice appears exactly the same from each of the discrete lattice points when looking in that chosen direction.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The Bravais lattice concept is used to formally define a *crystalline arrangement* and its (finite) frontiers.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] A crystal is made up of one or more atoms, called the *basis* or *motif*, at each lattice point.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The *basis* may consist of atoms, molecules, or polymer strings of solid matter, and the lattice provides the locations of the basis.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Two Bravais lattices are often considered equivalent if they have isomorphic symmetry groups.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In this sense, there are 5 possible Bravais lattices in 2-dimensional space and 14 possible Bravais lattices in 3-dimensional space.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The 14 possible symmetry groups of Bravais lattices are 14 of the 230 space groups.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In the context of the space group classification, the Bravais lattices are also called Bravais classes, Bravais arithmetic classes, or Bravais flocks.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In crystallography, there is the concept of a unit cell which comprises the space between adjacent lattice points as well as any atoms in that space.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] A unit cell is defined as a space that, when translated through a subset of all vectors described by $\mathbf {R} =n_{1}\mathbf {a} _{1}+n_{2}\mathbf {a} _{2}+n_{3}\mathbf {a} _{3}$ , fills the lattice space without overlapping or voids.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] There are mainly two types of unit cells: primitive unit cells and conventional unit cells.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] A primitive cell is the very smallest component of a lattice (or crystal) which, when stacked together with lattice translation operations, reproduces the whole lattice (or crystal).
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Note that the translations must be lattice translation operations that cause the lattice to appear unchanged after the translation.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] If arbitrary translations were allowed, one could make a primitive cell half the size of the true one, and translate twice as often, as an example.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In either definition, the primitive cell is characterized by its small size.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] There are clearly many choices of cell that can reproduce the whole lattice when stacked (two lattice halves, for instance), and the minimum size requirement distinguishes the primitive cell from all these other valid repeating units.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] If the lattice or crystal is 2-dimensional, the primitive cell has a minimum area; likewise in 3 dimensions the primitive cell has a minimum volume.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Despite this rigid minimum-size requirement, there is not one unique choice of primitive unit cell.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In fact, all cells whose borders are primitive translation vectors will be primitive unit cells.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The fact that there is not a unique choice of primitive translation vectors for a given lattice leads to the multiplicity of possible primitive unit cells.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Conventional unit cells, on the other hand, are not necessarily minimum-size cells.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] They are chosen purely for convenience and are often used for illustration purposes.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Primitive unit cells are defined as unit cells with the smallest volume for a given crystal.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] (A crystal is a lattice and a basis at every lattice point.) To have the smallest cell volume, a primitive unit cell must contain (1) only one lattice point and (2) the minimum amount of basis constituents (e.g., the minimum number of atoms in a basis).
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] For the former requirement, counting the number of lattice points in a unit cell is such that, if a lattice point is shared by *m* adjacent unit cells around that lattice point, then the point is counted as 1/*m*.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The latter requirement is necessary since there are crystals that can be described by more than one combination of a lattice and a basis.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] For example, a crystal, viewed as a lattice with a single kind of atom located at every lattice point (the simplest basis form), may also be viewed as a lattice with a basis of two atoms.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In this case, a primitive unit cell is a unit cell having only one lattice point in the first way of describing the crystal in order to ensure the smallest unit cell volume.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Among all possible primitive cells for a given crystal, an obvious primitive cell may be the parallelepiped formed by a chosen set of primitive translation vectors.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] (Again, these vectors must make a lattice with the minimum amount of basis constituents.) That is, the set of all points $\mathbf {r} =x_{1}\mathbf {a} _{1}+x_{2}\mathbf {a} _{2}+x_{3}\mathbf {a} _{3}$ where $0\leq x_{i}<1$ and $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ is the chosen primitive vector.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] This primitive cell does not always show the clear symmetry of a given crystal.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In this case, a conventional unit cell easily displaying the crystal symmetry is often used.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The conventional unit cell volume will be an integer-multiple of the primitive unit cell volume.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In two dimensions, any lattice can be specified by the length of its two primitive translation vectors and the angle between them.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] There are an infinite number of possible lattices one can describe in this way.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Some way to categorize different types of lattices is desired.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] One way to do so is to recognize that some lattices have inherent symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] One can impose conditions on the length of the primitive translation vectors and on the angle between them to produce various symmetric lattices.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] These symmetries themselves are categorized into different types, such as point groups (which includes mirror symmetries, inversion symmetries and rotation symmetries) and translational symmetries.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Thus, lattices can be categorized based on what point group or translational symmetry applies to them.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In two dimensions, the most basic point group corresponds to rotational invariance under 2π and π, or 1- and 2-fold rotational symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] This actually applies automatically to all 2D lattices, and is the most general point group.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Lattices contained in this group (technically all lattices, but conventionally all lattices that don't fall into any of the other point groups) are called oblique lattices.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Thus altogether there are 5 Bravais lattices in 2 dimensions.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Likewise, in 3 dimensions, there are 14 Bravais lattices: 1 general "wastebasket" category (triclinic) and 13 more categories.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] These 14 lattice types are classified by their point groups into 7 lattice systems (triclinic, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, cubic, rhombohedral, and hexagonal).
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In two-dimensional space there are 5 Bravais lattices, grouped into four lattice systems, shown in the table below.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Below each diagram is the Pearson symbol for that Bravais lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The unit cells are specified according to the relative lengths of the cell edges (*a* and *b*) and the angle between them (*θ*).
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The area of the unit cell can be calculated by evaluating the norm ‖**a** × **b**‖, where **a** and **b** are the lattice vectors.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In three-dimensional space there are 14 Bravais lattices.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] These are obtained by combining one of the seven lattice systems with one of the centering types.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Not all combinations of lattice systems and centering types are needed to describe all of the possible lattices, as it can be shown that several of these are in fact equivalent to each other.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] For example, the monoclinic I lattice can be described by a monoclinic C lattice by different choice of crystal axes.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Similarly, all A- or B-centred lattices can be described either by a C- or P-centering.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] This reduces the number of combinations to 14 conventional Bravais lattices, shown in the table below.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The unit cells are specified according to six lattice parameters which are the relative lengths of the cell edges (*a*, *b*, *c*) and the angles between them (*α*, *β*, *γ*), where *α* is the angle between *b* and *c*, *β* is the angle between *a* and *c*, and *γ* is the angle between *a* and *b*.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The volume of the unit cell can be calculated by evaluating the triple product **a** · (**b** × **c**), where **a**, **b**, and **c** are the lattice vectors.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Some basic information for the lattice systems and Bravais lattices in three dimensions is summarized in the diagram at the beginning of this page.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The seven sided polygon (heptagon) and the number 7 at the centre indicate the seven lattice systems.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] The inner heptagons indicate the lattice angles, lattice parameters, Bravais lattices and Schöenflies notations for the respective lattice systems.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] In four dimensions, there are 64 Bravais lattices.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Of these, 23 are primitive and 41 are centered.
[src:solid-state-physics/bravais-lattice] Ten Bravais lattices split into enantiomorphic pairs.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] In mathematics and solid state physics, the first **Brillouin zone** (named after Léon Brillouin) is a uniquely defined primitive cell in reciprocal space.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] In the same way the Bravais lattice is divided up into Wigner–Seitz cells in the real lattice, the reciprocal lattice is broken up into Brillouin zones.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] The boundaries of this cell are given by planes related to points on the reciprocal lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] The importance of the Brillouin zone stems from the description of waves in a periodic medium given by Bloch's theorem, in which it is found that the solutions can be completely characterized by their behavior in a single Brillouin zone.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] The first Brillouin zone is the locus of points in reciprocal space that are closer to the origin of the reciprocal lattice than they are to any other reciprocal lattice points (see the derivation of the Wigner–Seitz cell).
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] Another definition is as the set of points in *k*-space that can be reached from the origin without crossing any Bragg plane.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] Equivalently, this is the Voronoi cell around the origin of the reciprocal lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] There are also second, third, *etc.*, Brillouin zones, corresponding to a sequence of disjoint regions (all with the same volume) at increasing distances from the origin, but these are used less frequently.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] As a result, the *first* Brillouin zone is often called simply the *Brillouin zone*.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] In general, the *n*-th Brillouin zone consists of the set of points that can be reached from the origin by crossing exactly *n* − 1 distinct Bragg planes.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] A related concept is that of the **irreducible Brillouin zone**, which is the first Brillouin zone reduced by all of the symmetries in the point group of the lattice (point group of the crystal).
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] The concept of a Brillouin zone was developed by Léon Brillouin (1889–1969), a French physicist.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] Within the Brillouin zone, a *constant-energy surface* represents the loci of all the ${\vec {k}}$ -points (that is, all the electron momentum values) that have the same energy.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] The Fermi surface is a special constant-energy surface that separates the unfilled orbitals from the filled ones at zero Kelvin.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] Several points of high symmetry are of special interest – these are called critical points.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] Other lattices have different types of high-symmetry points.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] They can be found in the illustrations below for both three- and two-dimensional lattices.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] In two dimensions, the number of Bravais lattices reduces to five.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] In the following illustration, the corresponding Brillouin zones are delimited by red lines.
[src:solid-state-physics/brillouin-zone] For each lattice, the irreducible Brillouin zone is highlighted (blue) in accordance with the definitions of the symmetry points given in Refs. and .
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In crystallography, **crystal structure** is a description of the ordered arrangement of atoms, ions, or molecules in a crystalline material.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Ordered structures occur from the intrinsic nature of constituent particles to form symmetric patterns that repeat along the principal directions of three-dimensional space in matter.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The smallest group of particles in a material that constitutes this repeating pattern is the unit cell of the structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The unit cell completely reflects the symmetry and structure of the entire crystal, which is built up by repetitive translation of the unit cell along its principal axes.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The translation vectors define the nodes of the Bravais lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The lengths of principal axes/edges, of the unit cell and angles between them are lattice constants, also called *lattice parameters* or *cell parameters*.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The symmetry properties of a crystal are described by the concept of space groups.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All possible symmetric arrangements of particles in three-dimensional space may be described by 230 space groups.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The crystal structure and symmetry play a critical role in determining many physical properties, such as cleavage, electronic band structure, and optical transparency.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Crystal structure is described in terms of the geometry of the arrangement of particles in the unit cells.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The unit cell is defined as the smallest repeating unit having the full symmetry of the crystal structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The geometry of the unit cell is defined as a parallelepiped, providing six lattice parameters taken as the lengths of the cell edges (*a*, *b*, *c*) and the angles between them (α, β, γ).
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The positions of particles inside the unit cell are described by the fractional coordinates (*xi*, *yi*, *zi*) along the cell edges, measured from a reference point.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] It is thus only necessary to report the coordinates of a smallest asymmetric subset of particles, called the crystallographic asymmetric unit.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The asymmetric unit may be chosen so that it occupies the smallest physical space, which means that not all particles need to be physically located inside the boundaries given by the lattice parameters.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All other particles of the unit cell are generated by the symmetry operations that characterize the symmetry of the unit cell.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The collection of symmetry operations of the unit cell is expressed formally as the space group of the crystal structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Vectors and planes in a crystal lattice are described by the three-value Miller index notation.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This syntax uses the indices *h*, *k*, and *ℓ* as directional parameters.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] By definition, the syntax (*hkℓ*) denotes a plane that intercepts the three points *a*1/*h*, *a*2/*k*, and *a*3/*ℓ*, or some multiple thereof.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] That is, the Miller indices are proportional to the inverses of the intercepts of the plane with the unit cell (in the basis of the lattice vectors).
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] If one or more of the indices is zero, the planes do not intersect that axis (i.e., the intercept is "at infinity").
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] A plane containing a coordinate axis is translated to no longer contain that axis before its Miller indices are determined.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The Miller indices for a plane are integers with no common factors.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Negative indices are indicated with horizontal bars, as in (123).
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In an orthogonal coordinate system for a cubic cell, the Miller indices of a plane are the Cartesian components of a vector normal to the plane.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The crystallographic directions are geometric lines linking nodes (atoms, ions or molecules) of a crystal.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Likewise, the crystallographic planes are geometric *planes* linking nodes.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Some directions and planes have a higher density of nodes.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Some directions and planes are defined by symmetry of the crystal system.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In monoclinic, trigonal, tetragonal, and hexagonal systems there is one unique axis (sometimes called the **principal axis**) which has higher rotational symmetry than the other two axes.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The **basal plane** is the plane perpendicular to the principal axis in these crystal systems.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] For triclinic, orthorhombic, and cubic crystal systems the axis designation is arbitrary and there is no principal axis.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] For the special case of simple cubic crystals, the lattice vectors are orthogonal and of equal length (usually denoted *a*); similarly for the reciprocal lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] So, in this common case, the Miller indices (*ℓmn*) and [*ℓmn*] both simply denote normals/directions in Cartesian coordinates.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] For face-centered cubic (fcc) and body-centered cubic (bcc) lattices, the primitive lattice vectors are not orthogonal.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] However, in these cases the Miller indices are conventionally defined relative to the lattice vectors of the cubic supercell and hence are again simply the Cartesian directions.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The defining property of a crystal is its inherent symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Performing certain symmetry operations on the crystal lattice leaves it unchanged.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All crystals have translational symmetry in three directions, but some have other symmetry elements as well.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] For example, rotating the crystal 180° about a certain axis may result in an atomic configuration that is identical to the original configuration; the crystal has twofold rotational symmetry about this axis.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In addition to rotational symmetry, a crystal may have symmetry in the form of mirror planes, and also the so-called compound symmetries, which are a combination of translation and rotation or mirror symmetries.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] A full classification of a crystal is achieved when all inherent symmetries of the crystal are identified.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Lattice systems are a grouping of crystal structures according to the point groups of their lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All crystals fall into one of seven lattice systems.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] They are related to, but not the same as the seven crystal systems.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The most symmetric, the cubic or isometric system, has the symmetry of a cube, that is, it exhibits four threefold rotational axes oriented at 109.5° (the tetrahedral angle) with respect to each other.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] These threefold axes lie along the body diagonals of the cube.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The other six lattice systems, are hexagonal, tetragonal, rhombohedral (often confused with the trigonal crystal system), orthorhombic, monoclinic and triclinic which is the least symmetrical as it possess only identity (E).
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Bravais lattices, also referred to as *space lattices*, describe the geometric arrangement of the lattice points, and therefore the translational symmetry of the crystal.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The three dimensions of space afford 14 distinct Bravais lattices describing the translational symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All crystalline materials recognized today, not including quasicrystals, fit in one of these arrangements.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The fourteen three-dimensional lattices, classified by lattice system, are shown above.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The crystal structure consists of the same group of atoms, the *basis*, positioned around each and every lattice point.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This group of atoms therefore repeats indefinitely in three dimensions according to the arrangement of one of the Bravais lattices.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The characteristic rotation and mirror symmetries of the unit cell is described by its crystallographic point group.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Recent developments in crystallography and intermetallic materials science have led to the identification of a new family of ternary compounds known as ZIP phases.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] These structures are characterised by so-called dualistic atomic ordering, in which different atomic sublattices display distinct ordering behaviour within a single crystal lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] A crystal system is a set of point groups in which the point groups themselves and their corresponding space groups are assigned to a lattice system.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Of the 32 point groups that exist in three dimensions, most are assigned to only one lattice system, in which case the crystal system and lattice system both have the same name.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] However, five point groups are assigned to two lattice systems, rhombohedral and hexagonal, because both lattice systems exhibit threefold rotational symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] These point groups are assigned to the trigonal crystal system.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In total there are seven crystal systems: triclinic, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, trigonal, hexagonal, and cubic.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The crystallographic point group or *crystal class* is the mathematical group comprising the symmetry operations that leave at least one point unmoved and that leave the appearance of the crystal structure unchanged.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Rotation axes (proper and improper), reflection planes, and centers of symmetry are collectively called *symmetry elements*.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Each one can be classified into one of the seven crystal systems.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In addition to the operations of the point group, the space group of the crystal structure contains translational symmetry operations.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] By considering the arrangement of atoms relative to each other, their coordination numbers, interatomic distances, types of bonding, etc., it is possible to form a general view of the structures and alternative ways of visualizing them.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The principles involved can be understood by considering the most efficient way of packing together equal-sized spheres and stacking close-packed atomic planes in three dimensions.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] For example, if plane A lies beneath plane B, there are two possible ways of placing an additional atom on top of layer B.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The unit cell of a ccp arrangement of atoms is the face-centered cubic (fcc) unit cell.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This is not immediately obvious, as the closely packed layers are parallel to the {111} planes of the fcc unit cell.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] There are four different orientations of the close-packed layers.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] One important characteristic of a crystalline structure is its atomic packing factor (APF).
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This is calculated by assuming that all the atoms are identical spheres, with a radius large enough that each sphere abuts on the next.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Another important characteristic of a crystalline structure is its coordination number (CN).
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This is the number of nearest neighbours of a central atom in the structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The 74% packing efficiency of the FCC and HCP is the maximum density possible in unit cells constructed of spheres of only one size.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Interstitial sites refer to the empty spaces in between the atoms in the crystal lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] These spaces can be filled by oppositely charged ions to form multi-element structures.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] They can also be filled by impurity atoms or self-interstitials to form interstitial defects.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Real crystals feature defects or irregularities in the ideal arrangements described above and it is these defects that critically determine many of the electrical and mechanical properties of real materials.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] When one atom substitutes for one of the principal atomic components within the crystal structure, alteration in the electrical and thermal properties of the material may ensue.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Impurities may also manifest as electron spin impurities in certain materials.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Dislocations in a crystal lattice are line defects that are associated with local stress fields.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Dislocations allow shear at lower stress than that needed for a perfect crystal structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The local stress fields result in interactions between the dislocations which then result in strain hardening or cold working.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Grain boundaries are interfaces where crystals of different orientations meet.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] A grain boundary is a single-phase interface, with crystals on each side of the boundary being identical except in orientation.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The term "crystallite boundary" is sometimes, though rarely, used.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Grain boundary areas contain those atoms that have been perturbed from their original lattice sites, dislocations, and impurities that have migrated to the lower energy grain boundary.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Treating a grain boundary geometrically as an interface of a single crystal cut into two parts, one of which is rotated, we see that there are five variables required to define a grain boundary.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The first two numbers come from the unit vector that specifies a rotation axis.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The third number designates the angle of rotation of the grain.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The final two numbers specify the plane of the grain boundary (or a unit vector that is normal to this plane).
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Grain boundaries disrupt the motion of dislocations through a material, so reducing crystallite size is a common way to improve strength, as described by the Hall–Petch relationship.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Since grain boundaries are defects in the crystal structure they tend to decrease the electrical and thermal conductivity of the material.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The high interfacial energy and relatively weak bonding in most grain boundaries often makes them preferred sites for the onset of corrosion and for the precipitation of new phases from the solid.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] They are also important to many of the mechanisms of creep.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Grain boundaries are in general only a few nanometers wide.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In common materials, crystallites are large enough that grain boundaries account for a small fraction of the material.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] However, very small grain sizes are achievable.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In nanocrystalline solids, grain boundaries become a significant volume fraction of the material, with profound effects on such properties as diffusion and plasticity.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In the limit of small crystallites, as the volume fraction of grain boundaries approaches 100%, the material ceases to have any crystalline character, and thus becomes an amorphous solid.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The difficulty of predicting stable crystal structures based on the knowledge of only the chemical composition has long been a stumbling block on the way to fully computational materials design.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Now, with more powerful algorithms and high-performance computing, structures of medium complexity can be predicted using such approaches as evolutionary algorithms, random sampling, or metadynamics.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The crystal structures of simple ionic solids (e.g., NaCl or table salt) have long been rationalized in terms of Pauling's rules, first set out in 1929 by Linus Pauling, referred to by many since as the "father of the chemical bond".
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Pauling also considered the nature of the interatomic forces in metals, and concluded that about half of the five d-orbitals in the transition metals are involved in bonding, with the remaining nonbonding d-orbitals being responsible for the magnetic properties.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Pauling was therefore able to correlate the number of d-orbitals in bond formation with the bond length, as well as with many of the physical properties of the substance.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] He subsequently introduced the metallic orbital, an extra orbital necessary to permit uninhibited resonance of valence bonds among various electronic structures.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In the resonating valence bond theory, the factors that determine the choice of one from among alternative crystal structures of a metal or intermetallic compound revolve around the energy of resonance of bonds among interatomic positions.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] It is clear that some modes of resonance would make larger contributions (be more mechanically stable than others), and that in particular a simple ratio of number of bonds to number of positions would be exceptional.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The resulting principle is that a special stability is associated with the simplest ratios or "bond numbers": 1⁄2, 1⁄3, 2⁄3, 1⁄4, 3⁄4, etc.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The choice of structure and the value of the axial ratio (which determines the relative bond lengths) are thus a result of the effort of an atom to use its valency in the formation of stable bonds with simple fractional bond numbers.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This treatment thus emphasized the increasing bond strength as a function of group number.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The operation of directional forces were emphasized in one article on the relation between bond hybrids and the metallic structures.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The resulting correlation between electronic and crystalline structures is summarized by a single parameter, the weight of the d-electrons per hybridized metallic orbital.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The "d-weight" calculates out to 0.5, 0.7 and 0.9 for the fcc, hcp and bcc structures respectively.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The relationship between d-electrons and crystal structure thus becomes apparent.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In crystal structure predictions/simulations, the periodicity is usually applied, since the system is imagined as being unlimited in all directions.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Polymorphism is the occurrence of multiple crystalline forms of a material.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] It is found in many crystalline materials including polymers, minerals, and metals.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] According to Gibbs' rules of phase equilibria, these unique crystalline phases are dependent on intensive variables such as pressure and temperature.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Polymorphism is related to allotropy, which refers to elemental solids.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The complete morphology of a material is described by polymorphism and other variables such as crystal habit, amorphous fraction or crystallographic defects.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Polymorphs have different stabilities and may spontaneously and irreversibly transform from a metastable form (or thermodynamically unstable form) to the stable form at a particular temperature.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] They also exhibit different melting points, solubilities, and X-ray diffraction patterns.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] One good example of this is the quartz form of silicon dioxide, or SiO2.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In the vast majority of silicates, the Si atom shows tetrahedral coordination by 4 oxygens.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All but one of the crystalline forms involve tetrahedral {SiO4} units linked together by shared vertices in different arrangements.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In different minerals the tetrahedra show different degrees of networking and polymerization.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] For example, they occur singly, joined in pairs, in larger finite clusters including rings, in chains, double chains, sheets, and three-dimensional frameworks.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The minerals are classified into groups based on these structures.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] In each of the 7 thermodynamically stable crystalline forms or polymorphs of crystalline quartz, only 2 out of 4 of each the edges of the {SiO4} tetrahedra are shared with others, yielding the net chemical formula for silica: SiO2.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Another example is elemental tin (Sn), which is malleable near ambient temperatures but is brittle when cooled.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This change in mechanical properties due to existence of its two major allotropes, α- and β-tin.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] The two allotropes that are encountered at normal pressure and temperature, α-tin and β-tin, are more commonly known as *gray tin* and *white tin* respectively.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Two more allotropes, γ and σ, exist at temperatures above 161 °C and pressures above several GPa.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] White tin is metallic, and is the stable crystalline form at or above room temperature.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Below 13.2 °C, tin exists in the gray form, which has a diamond cubic crystal structure, similar to diamond, silicon or germanium.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Gray tin has no metallic properties at all, is a dull gray powdery material, and has few uses, other than a few specialized semiconductor applications.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Although the α–β transformation temperature of tin is nominally 13.2 °C, impurities (e.g.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Al, Zn, etc.) lower the transition temperature well below 0 °C, and upon addition of Sb or Bi the transformation may not occur at all.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Twenty of the 32 crystal classes are piezoelectric, and crystals belonging to one of these classes (point groups) display piezoelectricity.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All piezoelectric classes lack inversion symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Any material develops a dielectric polarization when an electric field is applied, but a substance that has such a natural charge separation even in the absence of a field is called a polar material.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Whether or not a material is polar is determined solely by its crystal structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Only ten of the 32 point groups are polar.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] All polar crystals are pyroelectric, so the ten polar crystal classes are sometimes referred to as the pyroelectric classes.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] There are a few crystal structures, notably the perovskite structure, which exhibit ferroelectric behavior.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This is analogous to ferromagnetism, in that, in the absence of an electric field during production, the ferroelectric crystal does not exhibit a polarization.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] Upon the application of an electric field of sufficient magnitude, the crystal becomes permanently polarized.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] This polarization can be reversed by a sufficiently large counter-charge, in the same way that a ferromagnet can be reversed.
[src:solid-state-physics/crystal-lattice] However, although they are called ferroelectrics, the effect is due to the crystal structure (not the presence of a ferrous metal).
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In condensed matter physics, the **density of states** (**DOS**) of a system describes the number of allowed modes or states per unit energy range.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The density of states is defined as $D(E)=N(E)/V$ , where $N(E)\delta E$ is the number of states in the system of volume V whose energies lie in the range from E to $E+\delta E$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] It is mathematically represented as a distribution by a probability density function, and it is generally an average over the space and time domains of the various states occupied by the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The density of states is directly related to the dispersion relations of the properties of the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] High DOS at a specific energy level means that many states are available for occupation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Generally, the density of states of matter is continuous.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In isolated systems however, such as atoms or molecules in the gas phase, the density distribution is discrete, like a spectral density.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Local variations, most often due to distortions of the original system, are often referred to as **local densities of states** (LDOSs).
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In quantum mechanical systems, waves, or wave-like particles, can occupy modes or states with wavelengths and propagation directions dictated by the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] For example, in some systems, the interatomic spacing and the atomic charge of a material might allow only electrons of certain wavelengths to exist.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In other systems, the crystalline structure of a material might allow waves to propagate in one direction, while suppressing wave propagation in another direction.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Often, only specific states are permitted.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Thus, it can happen that many states are available for occupation at a specific energy level, while no states are available at other energy levels.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Looking at the density of states of electrons at the band edge between the valence and conduction bands in a semiconductor, for an electron in the conduction band, an increase of the electron energy makes more states available for occupation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Alternatively, the density of states is discontinuous for an interval of energy, which means that no states are available for electrons to occupy within the band gap of the material.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This condition also means that an electron at the conduction band edge must lose at least the band gap energy of the material in order to transition to another state in the valence band.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This determines if the material is an insulator or a metal in the dimension of the propagation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The result of the number of states in a band is also useful for predicting the conduction properties.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] For example, in a one dimensional crystalline structure an odd number of electrons per atom results in a half-filled top band; there are free electrons at the Fermi level resulting in a metal.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] On the other hand, an even number of electrons exactly fills a whole number of bands, leaving the rest empty.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] If then the Fermi level lies in an occupied band gap between the highest occupied state and the lowest empty state, the material will be an insulator or semiconductor.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Depending on the quantum mechanical system, the density of states can be calculated for electrons, photons, or phonons, and can be given as a function of either energy or the wave vector *k*.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] To convert between the DOS as a function of the energy and the DOS as a function of the wave vector, the system-specific energy dispersion relation between *E* and *k* must be known.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In general, the topological properties of the system such as the band structure, have a major impact on the properties of the density of states.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The most well-known systems, like neutron matter in neutron stars and free electron gases in metals (examples of degenerate matter and a Fermi gas), have a 3-dimensional Euclidean topology.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Less familiar systems, like two-dimensional electron gases (2DEG) in graphite layers and the quantum Hall effect system in MOSFET type devices, have a 2-dimensional Euclidean topology.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Even less familiar are carbon nanotubes, the quantum wire and Luttinger liquid with their 1-dimensional topologies.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Systems with 1D and 2D topologies are likely to become more common, assuming developments in nanotechnology and materials science proceed.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] For isotropic one-dimensional systems with parabolic energy dispersion, the density of states is ${\textstyle D_{1D}(E)={\tfrac {1}{2\pi \hbar }}({\tfrac {2m}{E}})^{1/2}}$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The number of states with energy $E'$ (degree of degeneracy) is given by: $g\left(E'\right)=\lim _{\Delta E\to 0}\int _{E'}^{E'+\Delta E}D(E)\,\mathrm {d} E=\lim _{\Delta E\to 0}D\left(E'\right)\Delta E,$ where the last equality only applies when the mean value theorem for integrals is valid.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] There is a large variety of systems and types of states for which DOS calculations can be done.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Some condensed matter systems possess a structural symmetry on the microscopic scale which can be exploited to simplify calculation of their densities of states.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In spherically symmetric systems, the integrals of functions are one-dimensional because all variables in the calculation depend only on the radial parameter of the dispersion relation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Fluids, glasses and amorphous solids are examples of a symmetric system whose dispersion relations have a rotational symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Measurements on powders or polycrystalline samples require evaluation and calculation functions and integrals over the whole domain, most often a Brillouin zone, of the dispersion relations of the system of interest.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Sometimes the symmetry of the system is high, which causes the shape of the functions describing the dispersion relations of the system to appear many times over the whole domain of the dispersion relation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In such cases the effort to calculate the DOS can be reduced by a great amount when the calculation is limited to a reduced zone or fundamental domain.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The Brillouin zone of the face-centered cubic lattice (FCC) in the figure on the right has the 48-fold symmetry of the point group *Oh* with full octahedral symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This configuration means that the integration over the whole domain of the Brillouin zone can be reduced to a 48-th part of the whole Brillouin zone.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] As a crystal structure periodic table shows, there are many elements with a FCC crystal structure, like diamond, silicon and platinum and their Brillouin zones and dispersion relations have this 48-fold symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Two other familiar crystal structures are the body-centered cubic lattice (BCC) and hexagonal closed packed structures (HCP) with cubic and hexagonal lattices, respectively.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The BCC structure has the 24-fold pyritohedral symmetry of the point group *Th*.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The HCP structure has the 12-fold prismatic dihedral symmetry of the point group *D3h*.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] A complete list of symmetry properties of a point group can be found in point group character tables.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In general it is easier to calculate a DOS when the symmetry of the system is higher and the number of topological dimensions of the dispersion relation is lower.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The DOS of dispersion relations with rotational symmetry can often be calculated analytically.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This result is fortunate, since many materials of practical interest, such as steel and silicon, have high symmetry.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In anisotropic condensed matter systems such as a single crystal of a compound, the density of states could be different in one crystallographic direction than in another.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] These causes the anisotropic density of states to be more difficult to visualize, and might require methods such as calculating the DOS for particular points or directions only, or calculating the projected density of states (PDOS) to a particular crystal orientation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The density of states is dependent upon the dimensional limits of the object itself.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In a system described by three orthogonal parameters (3 Dimension), the units of DOS is [Energy]−1[Volume]−1, in a two dimensional system, the units of DOS is [Energy]−1[Area]−1, in a one dimensional system, the units of DOS is [Energy]−1[Length]−1.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The referenced volume is the volume of *k*-space; the space enclosed by the constant energy surface of the system derived through a dispersion relation that relates *E* to *k*.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] An example of a 3-dimensional *k*-space is given in Fig.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] It can be seen that the dimensionality of the system confines the momentum of particles inside the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The calculation for DOS starts by counting the *N* allowed states at a certain *k* that are contained within [*k*, *k* + d*k*] inside the volume of the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This procedure is done by differentiating the whole k-space volume $\Omega _{n,k}$ in n-dimensions at an arbitrary *k*, with respect to *k*.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] for a *n*-dimensional *k*-space with the topologically determined constants $c_{1}=2,\ c_{2}=\pi ,\ c_{3}={\frac {4\pi }{3}}$ for linear, disk and spherical symmetrical shaped functions in 1, 2 and 3-dimensional Euclidean *k*-spaces respectively.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] One state is large enough to contain particles having wavelength λ.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In a quantum system the length of λ will depend on a characteristic spacing of the system L that is confining the particles.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Finally the density of states *N* is multiplied by a factor $s/V_{k}$ , where *s* is a constant degeneracy factor that accounts for internal degrees of freedom due to such physical phenomena as spin or polarization.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] If no such phenomenon is present then $s=1$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] *Vk* is the volume in k-space whose wavevectors are smaller than the smallest possible wavevectors decided by the characteristic spacing of the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] To finish the calculation for DOS find the number of states per unit sample volume at an energy E inside an interval $[E,E+\mathrm {d} E]$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The general form of DOS of a system is given as $D_{n}\left(E\right)={\frac {\mathrm {d} \Omega _{n}(E)}{\mathrm {d} E}}$ The scheme sketched so far *only* applies to *monotonically rising* and *spherically symmetric* dispersion relations.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In general the dispersion relation $E(k)$ is not spherically symmetric and in many cases it isn't continuously rising either.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] To express *D* as a function of *E* the inverse of the dispersion relation $E(k)$ has to be substituted into the expression of $\Omega _{n}(k)$ as a function of *k* to get the expression of $\Omega _{n}(E)$ as a function of the energy.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] If the dispersion relation is not spherically symmetric or continuously rising and can't be inverted easily then in most cases the DOS has to be calculated numerically.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] More detailed derivations are available.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The dispersion relation for electrons in a solid is given by the electronic band structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The kinetic energy of a particle depends on the magnitude and direction of the wave vector *k*, the properties of the particle and the environment in which the particle is moving.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The dispersion relation is a spherically symmetric parabola and it is continuously rising so the DOS can be calculated easily.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This expression is a kind of dispersion relation because it interrelates two wave properties and it is isotropic because only the length and not the direction of the wave vector appears in the expression.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In 1-dimensional systems the DOS diverges at the bottom of the band as E drops to $E_{0}$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In 2-dimensional systems the DOS turns out to be independent of E .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Finally for 3-dimensional systems the DOS rises as the square root of the energy.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] where V is the total volume, and $N(E-E_{0})$ includes the 2-fold spin degeneracy.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The density of states plays an important role in the kinetic theory of solids.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The product of the density of states and the probability distribution function is the number of occupied states per unit volume at a given energy for a system in thermal equilibrium.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This value is widely used to investigate various physical properties of matter.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The following are examples, using two common distribution functions, of how applying a distribution function to the density of states can give rise to physical properties.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Fermi–Dirac statistics: The Fermi–Dirac probability distribution function, Fig.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] 4, is used to find the probability that a fermion occupies a specific quantum state in a system at thermal equilibrium.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Fermions are particles which obey the Pauli exclusion principle (e.g. electrons, protons, neutrons).
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] $\mu$ is the chemical potential (also denoted as EF and called the Fermi level when *T*=0), $k_{\mathrm {B} }$ is the Boltzmann constant, and T is temperature.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] 4 illustrates how the product of the Fermi-Dirac distribution function and the three-dimensional density of states for a semiconductor can give insight to physical properties such as carrier concentration and Energy band gaps.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Bose–Einstein statistics: The Bose–Einstein distribution function $f_{\mathrm {BE} }(E)$ is the average number of bosons occupying any quantum state with energy E in a system at thermal equilibrium.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Bosons are particles which do not obey the Pauli exclusion principle (e.g. phonons and photons), so $f_{\mathrm {BE} }(E)$ can be greater than 1.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] From these two distributions it is possible to calculate properties such as the internal energy per unit volume u , the number of particles N , specific heat capacity c , and thermal conductivity k .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] d is dimensionality, $\nu$ is sound velocity and $\Lambda$ is mean free path.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The density of states appears in many areas of physics, and helps to explain a number of quantum mechanical phenomena.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Calculating the density of states for small structures shows that the distribution of electrons changes as dimensionality is reduced.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] For quantum wires, the DOS for certain energies actually becomes higher than the DOS for bulk semiconductors, and for quantum dots the electrons become quantized to certain energies.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The photon density of states can be manipulated by using periodic structures with length scales on the order of the wavelength of light.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Some structures can completely inhibit the propagation of light of certain colors (energies), creating a photonic band gap: the DOS is zero for those photon energies.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Other structures can inhibit the propagation of light only in certain directions to create mirrors, waveguides, and cavities.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Such periodic structures are known as photonic crystals.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In nanostructured media the concept of local density of states (LDOS) is often more relevant than that of DOS, as the DOS varies considerably from point to point.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Interesting systems are in general complex, for instance compounds, biomolecules, polymers, etc.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Because of the complexity of these systems the analytical calculation of the density of states is in most of the cases impossible.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Computer simulations offer a set of algorithms to evaluate the density of states with a high accuracy.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] One of these algorithms is called the Wang and Landau algorithm.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Within the Wang and Landau scheme any previous knowledge of the density of states is required.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] One proceeds as follows: the cost function (for example the energy) of the system is discretized.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Each time the bin *i* is reached one updates a histogram for the density of states, $g(i)$ , by $g(i)\rightarrow g(i)+f$ where *f* is called the modification factor.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] As soon as each bin in the histogram is visited a certain number of times (10-15), the modification factor is reduced by some criterion, for instance, $f_{n+1}\rightarrow {\frac {1}{2}}f_{n}$ where *n* denotes the *n*-th update step.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The simulation finishes when the modification factor is less than a certain threshold, for instance $f_{n}<10^{-8}$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The Wang and Landau algorithm has some advantages over other common algorithms such as multicanonical simulations and parallel tempering.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] For example, the density of states is obtained as the main product of the simulation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Additionally, Wang and Landau simulations are completely independent of the temperature.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] This feature allows to compute the density of states of systems with very rough energy landscape such as proteins.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Mathematically the density of states is formulated in terms of a tower of covering maps.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] An important feature of the definition of the DOS is that it can be extended to any system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] One of its properties are the translationally invariability which means that the density of the states is homogeneous and it's the same at each point of the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] But this is just a particular case and the LDOS gives a wider description with a heterogeneous density of states through the system.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] the factor of $|\phi _{j}(x)|^{2}$ means that each state contributes more in the regions where the density is high.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] An average over x of this expression will restore the usual formula for a DOS.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The LDOS is useful in inhomogeneous systems, where $n(E,x)$ contains more information than $n(E)$ alone.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] this is called the *spectral function* and it's a function with each wave function separately in its own variable.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In more advanced theory it is connected with the Green's functions and provides a compact representation of some results such as optical absorption.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] LDOS can be used to gain profit into a solid-state device.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] For example, the figure on the right illustrates LDOS of a transistor as it turns on and off in a ballistic simulation.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] The LDOS has clear boundary in the source and drain, that corresponds to the location of band edge.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In the channel, the DOS is increasing as gate voltage increase and potential barrier goes down.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In optics and photonics, the concept of local density of states refers to the states that can be occupied by a photon.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] For light it is usually measured by fluorescence methods, near-field scanning methods or by cathodoluminescence techniques.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Different photonic structures have different LDOS behaviors with different consequences for spontaneous emission.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] In photonic crystals, near-zero LDOS are expected, inhibiting spontaneous emission.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] Similar LDOS enhancement is also expected in plasmonic cavity.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] However, in disordered photonic nanostructures, the LDOS behave differently.
[src:solid-state-physics/density-of-states] They fluctuate spatially with their statistics, and are proportional to the scattering strength of the structures.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] In solid-state physics, the **free electron model** is a quantum mechanical model for the behaviour of charge carriers in a metallic solid.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] It was developed in 1927, principally by Arnold Sommerfeld, who combined the classical Drude model with quantum mechanical Fermi–Dirac statistics and hence it is also known as the **Drude–Sommerfeld model**.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The free electron model solved many of the inconsistencies related to the Drude model and gave insight into several other properties of metals.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The free electron model considers that metals are composed of a quantum electron gas where ions play almost no role.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The model can be very predictive when applied to alkali and noble metals.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] In 1900, Paul Drude developed the Drude model of electrical conduction, which was refined by Hendrik Lorentz.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Drude model was successful in predicting Wiedemann–Franz law.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] However physicists like Albert Einstein and Max Reinganum quickly pointed out various problems.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] By 1911, it was the consensus that the Drude model provided an incorrect prediction of the heat capacity.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The same year, in his dissertation Niels Bohr pointed out that Drude model could not predict the diamagnetism of metals.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] In the same way, Karl Baedeker pointed out that all galvanomagnetic predictions were wrong.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] In 1924, the fourth Solvay Conference was organized about the problems with the Drude model.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] About this time, theories of degeneracy were being discussed.Einstein working with Satyendra Nath Bose, tried to apply the recently developed Bose–Einstein statistics to electrons in a metal but he showed it was not compatible.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] In 1925, Wolfgang Pauli proposed the exclusion principle for electrons.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Enrico Fermi and Paul Dirac came independently with Fermi–Dirac statistics in 1926.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Specially Fermi was motivated by the failures of the Drude model.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Arnold Sommerfeld became involved in the theory of metals during a meeting in University of Hamburg in the spring 1927.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] During the meeting, Pauli shared his work with Sommerfeld who quickly realized that the classical Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics of the Drude model could be the source of the issue.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] When Sommerfeld returned to the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München, he applied Fermi–Dirac statistics and found that the new prediction of Wiedemann–Franz law was even more accurate than the result of the Drude model.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] In the summer of 1927, Sommerfeld lectured about his result and showed that the specific heat problem was solved by using the right statistics.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] That year, he published his results in *Die Naturwissenschaften* and presented his conclusions during the Como Conference.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] After the conference, many physicists, including Yakov Frenkel, Fermi, Georg Joos and Walter Schottky, continued to discuss the model with Sommerfeld by mail.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] During winter 1927/1928 he gave a lecture to his students, including Rudolf Peierls, Carl Eckart, William V.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Sommerfeld wrote a two-part treatise on the topic in *Zeitschrift für Physik* in 1928.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] At least, 14 other articles were published that year on the topic in that journal, including equations for field electron emission developed by Lothar Wolfgang Nordheim, student of Sommerfeld and Ralph H.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Sommerfeld nevertheless promoted his work in a trip to Japan in 1928 and to the United States in 1931.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] John Bardeen, who later developed the transistor, attended Sommerfeld's lecture on the free electron model in Wisconsin.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Sommerfeld also wrote a review of the model in 1931 with Nathaniel H.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] And included a chapter in 1933 *Handbuch der Physik* with Bethe.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] A major breakthrough with respect to the Drude and free electron models came in 1928, with Felix Bloch dissertation, under the supervision of Werner Heisenberg.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Bloch's theorem introduced the electron wave behavior and made use of the lattice periodicity.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Contrary to Sommerfeld's semi-classical model, Bloch's theory was the first time that the electron was treated quantum mechanically using the recently developed quantum mechanics by Heisenberg and Erwin Schrödinger.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Bethe, years later, wrote that he believed in Sommerfeld until the work of Felix Bloch appeared.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The name of the model comes from the first two assumptions, as each electron can be treated as free particle with a respective quadratic relation between energy and momentum.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Effective masses can be derived from band structure computations that were not originally taken into account in the free electron model.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Many physical properties follow directly from the Drude model, as some equations do not depend on the statistical distribution of the particles.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Taking the classical velocity distribution of an ideal gas or the velocity distribution of a Fermi gas only changes the results related to the speed of the electrons.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] where $\mathbf {J}$ is the current density, $\mathbf {E}$ is the external electric field, n is the electronic density (number of electrons/volume), $\tau$ is the mean free time and e is the electron electric charge.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Other quantities that remain the same under the free electron model as under Drude's are the AC susceptibility, the plasma frequency, the magnetoresistance, and the Hall coefficient related to the Hall effect.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Many properties of the free electron model follow directly from equations related to the Fermi gas, as the independent electron approximation leads to an ensemble of non-interacting electrons.
