[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] This pressure is called the electron degeneracy pressure and does not come from repulsion or motion of the electrons but from the restriction that no more than two electrons (due to the two values of spin) can occupy the same energy level.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] This expression gives the right order of magnitude for the bulk modulus for alkali metals and noble metals, which show that this pressure is as important as other effects inside the metal.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] For other metals the crystalline structure has to be taken into account.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] According to the Bohr–Van Leeuwen theorem, a classical system at thermodynamic equilibrium cannot have a magnetic response.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The magnetic properties of matter in terms of a microscopic theory are purely quantum mechanical.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] where ${\textstyle \mu _{0}}$ is the vacuum permittivity and the ${\textstyle \mu _{\rm {B}}}$ is the Bohr magneton.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] This value results from the competition of two contributions: a diamagnetic contribution (known as Landau's diamagnetism) coming from the orbital motion of the electrons in the presence of a magnetic field, and a paramagnetic contribution (Pauli's paramagnetism).
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The latter contribution is three times larger in absolute value than the diamagnetic contribution and comes from the electron spin, an intrinsic quantum degree of freedom that can take two discrete values and it is associated to the electron magnetic moment.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] One open problem in solid-state physics before the arrival of quantum mechanics was to understand the heat capacity of metals.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] While most solids had a constant volumetric heat capacity given by Dulong–Petit law of about $3nk_{\rm {B}}$ at large temperatures, it did correctly predict its behavior at low temperatures.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] In the case of metals that are good conductors, it was expected that the electrons contributed also the heat capacity.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] If this was the case, the heat capacity of a metals should be 1.5 of that obtained by the Dulong–Petit law.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Nevertheless, such a large additional contribution to the heat capacity of metals was never measured, raising suspicions about the argument above.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] where the prefactor to $nk_{B}$ is considerably smaller than the 3/2 found in ${\textstyle c_{V}^{\text{Drude}}}$ , about 100 times smaller at room temperature and much smaller at lower ${\textstyle T}$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Evidently, the electronic contribution alone does not predict the Dulong–Petit law, i.e. the observation that the heat capacity of a metal is still constant at high temperatures.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] The free electron model can be improved in this sense by adding the contribution of the vibrations of the crystal lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/free-electron-model] Two famous quantum corrections include the Einstein solid model and the more refined Debye model.
