[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Each lattice point $(hk\ell )$ in the reciprocal lattice corresponds to a set of lattice planes $(hk\ell )$ in the real space lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] (A lattice plane is a plane crossing lattice points.) The direction of the reciprocal lattice vector corresponds to the normal to the real space planes.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The magnitude of the reciprocal lattice vector $\mathbf {K} _{m}$ is given in reciprocal length and is equal to the reciprocal of the interplanar spacing of the real space planes.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The formula for n dimensions can be derived assuming an n -dimensional real vector space V with a basis $(\mathbf {a} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {a} _{n})$ and an inner product $g\colon V\times V\to \mathbf {R}$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice vectors are uniquely determined by the formula $g(\mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {b} _{j})=2\pi \delta _{ij}$ .
