[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Reciprocal lattices for the cubic crystal system are as follows.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The simple cubic Bravais lattice, with cubic primitive cell of side a , has for its reciprocal a simple cubic lattice with a cubic primitive cell of side ${\textstyle {\frac {2\pi }{a}}}$ (or ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{a}}}$ in the crystallographer's definition).
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The cubic lattice is therefore said to be self-dual, having the same symmetry in reciprocal space as in real space.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice to an FCC lattice is the body-centered cubic (BCC) lattice, with a cube side of ${\textstyle {\frac {4\pi }{a}}}$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Locate a primitive unit cell of the FCC; i.e., a unit cell with one lattice point.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Now take one of the vertices of the primitive unit cell as the origin.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Give the basis vectors of the real lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Then from the known formulae, you can calculate the basis vectors of the reciprocal lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] These reciprocal lattice vectors of the FCC represent the basis vectors of a BCC real lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The basis vectors of a real BCC lattice and the reciprocal lattice of an FCC resemble each other in direction but not in magnitude.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice to a BCC lattice is the FCC lattice, with a cube side of ${\textstyle 4\pi /a}$ .
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The simple hexagonal lattice is therefore said to be self-dual, having the same symmetry in reciprocal space as in real space.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] One path to the reciprocal lattice of an arbitrary collection of atoms comes from the idea of scattered waves in the Fraunhofer (long-distance or lens back-focal-plane) limit as a Huygens-style sum of amplitudes from all points of scattering (in this case from each individual atom).
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Here **g** = **q**/(2π) is the scattering vector **q** in crystallographer units, *N* is the number of atoms, *f**j*[**g**] is the atomic scattering factor for atom *j* and scattering vector **g**, while **r***j* is the vector position of atom *j*.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The Fourier phase depends on one's choice of coordinate origin.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] when there are *j* = 1,*m* atoms inside the unit cell whose fractional lattice indices are respectively {*u**j*, *v**j*, *w**j*}.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] To consider effects due to finite crystal size, of course, a shape convolution for each point or the equation above for a finite lattice must be used instead.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Whether the array of atoms is finite or infinite, one can also imagine an "intensity reciprocal lattice" I[**g**], which relates to the amplitude lattice F via the usual relation *I* = *F***F* where *F** is the complex conjugate of F.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Since Fourier transformation is reversible, of course, this act of conversion to intensity tosses out "all except 2nd moment" (i.e. the phase) information.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Here **r***jk* is the vector separation between atom *j* and atom *k*.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] One can also use this to predict the effect of nano-crystallite shape, and subtle changes in beam orientation, on detected diffraction peaks even if in some directions the cluster is only one atom thick.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] On the down side, scattering calculations using the reciprocal lattice basically consider an incident plane wave.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Thus after a first look at reciprocal lattice (kinematic scattering) effects, beam broadening and multiple scattering (i.e. dynamical) effects may be important to consider as well.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] There are actually two versions in mathematics of the abstract dual lattice concept, for a given lattice *L* in a real vector space *V*, of finite dimension.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The first, which generalises directly the reciprocal lattice construction, uses Fourier analysis.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] It may be stated simply in terms of Pontryagin duality.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The dual group *V*^ to *V* is again a real vector space, and its closed subgroup *L*^ dual to *L* turns out to be a lattice in *V*^.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Therefore, *L*^ is the natural candidate for *dual lattice*, in a different vector space (of the same dimension).
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The other aspect is seen in the presence of a quadratic form *Q* on *V*; if it is non-degenerate it allows an identification of the dual space *V** of *V* with *V*.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The relation of *V** to *V* is not intrinsic; it depends on a choice of Haar measure (volume element) on *V*.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] But given an identification of the two, which is in any case well-defined up to a scalar, the presence of *Q* allows one to speak to the dual lattice to *L* while staying within *V*.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] In mathematics, the dual lattice of a given lattice *L* in an abelian locally compact topological group *G* is the subgroup *L*∗ of the dual group of *G* consisting of all continuous characters that are equal to one at each point of *L*.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] In discrete mathematics, a lattice is a locally discrete set of points described by all integral linear combinations of dim = *n* linearly independent vectors in **R***n*.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] The dual lattice is then defined by all points in the linear span of the original lattice (typically all of **R***n*) with the property that an integer results from the inner product with all elements of the original lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] It follows that the dual of the dual lattice is the original lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] Furthermore, if we allow the matrix *B* to have columns as the linearly independent vectors that describe the lattice, then the matrix $A=B\left(B^{\mathsf {T}}B\right)^{-1}$ has columns of vectors that describe the dual lattice.
[src:solid-state-physics/reciprocal-lattice] In quantum physics, reciprocal space is closely related to *momentum space* according to the proportionality $\mathbf {p} =\hbar \mathbf {k}$ , where $\mathbf {p}$ is the momentum vector and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Solid materials are formed from densely packed atoms, which interact intensely.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] These interactions produce the mechanical (e.g. hardness and elasticity), thermal, electrical, magnetic and optical properties of solids.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Depending on the material involved and the conditions in which it was formed, the atoms may be arranged in a regular, geometric pattern (crystalline solids, which include metals and ordinary water ice) or irregularly (an amorphous solid such as common window glass).
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The bulk of solid-state physics, as a general theory, is focused on crystals.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Primarily, this is because the periodicity of atoms in a crystal – its defining characteristic – facilitates mathematical modeling.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Likewise, crystalline materials often have electrical, magnetic, optical, or mechanical properties that can be exploited for engineering purposes.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The forces between the atoms in a crystal can take a variety of forms.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] For example, in a crystal of sodium chloride (common salt), the crystal is made up of ionic sodium and chlorine, and held together with ionic bonds.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] In others, the atoms share electrons and form covalent bonds.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] In metals, electrons are shared amongst the whole crystal in metallic bonding.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Finally, the noble gases do not undergo any of these types of bonding.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] In solid form, the noble gases are held together with van der Waals forces resulting from the polarisation of the electronic charge cloud on each atom.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The differences between the types of solid result from the differences between their bonding.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The DSSP catered to industrial physicists, and solid-state physics became associated with the technological applications made possible by research on solids.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] By the early 1960s, the DSSP was the largest division of the American Physical Society.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Large communities of solid state physicists also emerged in Europe after World War II, in particular in England, Germany, and the Soviet Union.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] In the United States and Europe, solid state became a prominent field through its investigations into semiconductors, superconductivity, nuclear magnetic resonance, and diverse other phenomena.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Today, solid-state physics is broadly considered to be the subfield of condensed matter physics, often referred to as hard condensed matter, that focuses on the properties of solids with regular crystal lattices.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Many properties of materials are affected by their crystal structure.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] This structure can be investigated using a range of crystallographic techniques, including X-ray crystallography, neutron diffraction and electron diffraction.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The sizes of the individual crystals in a crystalline solid material vary depending on the material involved and the conditions when it was formed.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Most crystalline materials encountered in everyday life are polycrystalline, with the individual crystals being microscopic in scale, but macroscopic single crystals can be produced either naturally (e.g. diamonds) or artificially.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Real crystals feature defects or irregularities in the ideal arrangements, and it is these defects that critically determine many of the electrical and mechanical properties of real materials.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Properties of materials such as electrical conduction and heat capacity are investigated by solid state physics.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] An early model of electrical conduction was the Drude model, which applied kinetic theory to the electrons in a solid.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] By assuming that the material contains immobile positive ions and an "electron gas" of classical, non-interacting electrons, the Drude model was able to explain electrical and thermal conductivity and the Hall effect in metals, although it greatly overestimated the electronic heat capacity.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Arnold Sommerfeld combined the classical Drude model with quantum mechanics in the free electron model (or Drude-Sommerfeld model).
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Here, the electrons are modelled as a Fermi gas, a gas of particles which obey the quantum mechanical Fermi–Dirac statistics.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The free electron model gave improved predictions for the heat capacity of metals, however, it was unable to explain the existence of insulators.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The nearly free electron model is a modification of the free electron model which includes a weak periodic perturbation meant to model the interaction between the conduction electrons and the ions in a crystalline solid.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] By introducing the idea of electronic bands, the theory explains the existence of conductors, semiconductors and insulators.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The nearly free electron model rewrites the Schrödinger equation for the case of a periodic potential.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] The solutions in this case are known as Bloch states.
[src:solid-state-physics/solid-state-physics] Deviations from periodicity are treated by quantum mechanical perturbation theory.
